5-opus-failures/ ) examining scaling laws and AI models in the context of O=
penAI=E2=80=99s o1 model; it=E2=80=99s excellent. This comparison to Moore=
=E2=80=99s Law was one of my favorite bits:

Today=E2=80=99s debate on AI scaling laws is not dissimilar to the decades-=
long debate around compute scaling and Moore=E2=80=99s law. Anyone who trie=
s to measure CPU compute primarily by clock speed =E2=80=93 a common metric=
 used before the late 2000s around the time of the end of Dennard Scaling =
=E2=80=93 would argue that we have not made any progress at all since then.=
 In reality, compute has been advancing all along =E2=80=93 when we hit a w=
all on processor clock speed, the focus shifted to multi-core architectures=
 and other methods to drive performance, despite power density and cooling =
constraints=E2=80=A6

As with computer enthusiasts in 2004, mainstream analysts and journalists a=
re missing the forest for the trees: despite the slowing down of one trend,=
 the industry collectively remains moving forward at a breakneck pace due t=
o other new emerging paradigms that are ripe for scaling and expansion. It =
is possible to stack =E2=80=9Cscaling laws=E2=80=9D =E2=80=93 pre-training =
will become just one of the vectors of improvement, and the aggregate =E2=
=80=9Cscaling law=E2=80=9D will continue scaling just like Moore=E2=80=99s =
Law has over last 50+ years.

On to the Update:

GM Kills Cruise
---------------

From Bloomberg ( https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2024-12-10/gm-to-w=
ind-down-robotaxi-operations-once-championed-by-ceo-barra ) :

General Motors Co. Chief Executive Officer Mary Barra, clad in her signatur=
e leather jacket and masked up pandemic style, climbed into a Cruise robota=
xi named Tostada for her first autonomous ride almost three years ago. =E2=
=80=9COh my God,=E2=80=9D she exclaimed in a moment GM promoted with a vide=
o. =E2=80=9CThis is incredible.=E2=80=9D Now she is shutting down the busin=
ess, citing the high costs to develop the technology and build out a fleet =
of cars in multiple cities, retreating from a once-promising market that pr=
oved full of reputational pitfalls for the automaker.

Instead, Barra will merge Cruise into GM=E2=80=99s operations with more hum=
ble goals such as developing advanced safety systems for the vehicles it se=
lls and, one day, offering autonomous driving as a feature on future models=
. With the decision to downgrade Cruise, GM is giving up on hopes of transf=
orming itself into a multi-platform technology company that targeted bringi=
ng in $50 billion in revenue from robotaxi fares and subscriptions by 2030.=
 The carmaker had aspired to double its revenue by 2030 on the twin pillars=
 of autonomy and electric vehicles. That goal also now looks remote without=
 Cruise as a new business and after GM scaled-back its lofty EV sales ambit=
ions=E2=80=A6

While GM will develop autonomous technology, it=E2=80=99s a big retrench fo=
r the company. The Detroit carmaker set out to recast itself a decade ago a=
s more than a mere metal-bender in an ambitious drive to stay competitive w=
ith Silicon Valley=E2=80=99s software giants in the race for robotaxis. The=
 move was unexpected after Cruise had managed to survive a shakeout among a=
utonomous-driving companies and a robotaxi crisis of its own making.

=E2=80=9CSurvive=E2=80=9D is generous: GM put over $9 billion into Cruise, =
and I=E2=80=99m skeptical about just how much of Cruise=E2=80=99s technolog=
y is going to be transformative in terms of individual GM cars.

Fleets Versus Autonomy
----------------------

To zoom out, there are currently two primary approaches to self-driving =E2=
=80=94 fleets and true autonomy =E2=80=94 which you can analogize to the ol=
d thick-thin client distinction in personal computing. In the thin client c=
oncept there is a central server that does all of the processing, and is ac=
cessed via distributed devices that are, at least in theory, much lower cos=
t; thick clients put the processing on the distributed devices, which are m=
ore expensive but more capable.

In this analogy the fleet concept is like thin clients: there is an assumpt=
ion of a centralized operator that maps a given geographic area, deploys th=
e cars, and provides remote assistance if necessary; these costs are spread=
 out over the entire fleet. This model is theoretically more performant but=
 less flexible; Cruise and Waymo use the fleet concept.

The thick client analogy, meanwhile, is a car that does self-driving on its=
 own, without the assumption of high definition maps, a centralized operato=
r, or remote assistance. This is much harder to pull off, but has the poten=
tial to be much more flexible; Tesla and Comma.ai ( https://comma.ai/ ) use=
 the autonomous concept.

It=E2=80=99s not a perfect analogy; fleet-based self-driving cars do have t=
o operate on their own, and self-driving cars would certainly benefit from =
centralized services like high-definition mapping. What is kind of weird ab=
out self-driving cars is that it is the fleet concept that is associated wi=
th higher costs in terms of hardware requirements, thanks to the use of a w=
ider array of sensors, while the companies focused on pure autonomy are mos=
tly using cameras.

The different cost structures are less weird when you think about the ideal=
 business model for these two approaches. A fleet concept is inherently cen=
tralized, which is exactly what you would want for a robotaxi service (give=
n that you need a centralized service for customers to access); a robotaxi =
service, meanwhile, needs maximum reliability and safety, while also having=
 the potential for superior utilization of the cars themselves, which helps=
 allay the additional costs. An autonomous car, meanwhile, makes sense for =
the autonomous individual, who wants to be able to go anywhere; this approa=
ch can be more lax in terms of safety, given there is a potential driver al=
ways at hand, but it also has to be relatively inexpensive, so that the ind=
ividual can afford the car.

There are further implications that arise from these different business mod=
els. Start with autonomy: the ideal solution it is likely to be a fully int=
egrated one, given that is serving the consumer market, where integrated pr=
oducts do better ( https://stratechery.com/2013/clayton-christensen-got-wro=
ng/?access_token=3DeyJhbGciOiJSUzI1NiIsImtpZCI6InN0cmF0ZWNoZXJ5LnBhc3Nwb3J0=
Lm9ubGluZSIsInR5cCI6IkpXVCJ9.eyJhdWQiOiJzdHJhdGVjaGVyeS5wYXNzcG9ydC5vbmxpbm=
UiLCJhenAiOiJIS0xjUzREd1Nod1AyWURLYmZQV00xIiwiZW50Ijp7InVyaSI6WyJodHRwczovL=
3N0cmF0ZWNoZXJ5LmNvbS8yMDEzL2NsYXl0b24tY2hyaXN0ZW5zZW4tZ290LXdyb25nLyJdfSwi=
ZXhwIjoxNzM2NTE2MjM5LCJpYXQiOjE3MzM5MjQyMzksImlzcyI6Imh0dHBzOi8vYXBpLnBhc3N=
wb3J0Lm9ubGluZS9vYXV0aCIsInNjb3BlIjoiZmVlZDpyZWFkIGFydGljbGU6cmVhZCBhc3NldD=
pyZWFkIGNhdGVnb3J5OnJlYWQgZW50aXRsZW1lbnRzIiwic3ViIjoiUnNldVlFOGpnSGVQcFdKZ=
jFmQWI0QyIsInVzZSI6ImFjY2VzcyJ9.rZo1z1dIx2bgDHGhVdbpzoaLUDAEVoIZY0gXRoKwDSV=
K43qgaSk7KGxjOPEbOXKiOcOQOdvweZ8HvDSKBMTddwWLQEz1GdHSfuno3FujfaasgHinAOGoLJ=
Jx7r4LFrzLggqwNY9_W9KyChxgXjTmJnPtBma43IXZJxpUAU6K7Xzx1PNaqHww1ZAk01ZeKv6wZ=
th6ypMvxvwO0gI0tsY665ipO8_9JaGGvFxZOtFarzuVNS0cE5Y73ZFL2yvhptXygyuvqd4vgJr4=
q4QPCvT5CYdanOZcC0I4hiesfGJK1vri3GaJA64cy-MzG36QmHc-ZAAgfe1TLbA9voapfBERLQ =
). An integrated solution also maximizes the reliability and functionality =
of the inexpensive hardware, enabling faster progress. This again, is obvio=
usly Tesla, although the other company I mentioned, Comma, is working on an=
 add-on system for existing cars that is quite obviously modular.

A robotaxi fleet, on the other hand, makes much more sense as a modular con=
cept; riders are choosing a service, not a car, so the user experience adva=
ntage of integration doesn=E2=80=99t really matter in the purchase decision=
. What is important is driving down prices, which means driving each level =
of the stack towards being a commodity; the part of the stack doing the com=
moditizing is the service layer, which ideally will have well defined inter=
faces for sensors, cars, fleet management, etc., spurring competition among=
st multiple providers.

This breakdown immediately exposes the flaw in GM=E2=80=99s entire approach=
: Cruise was seeking to be the service layer for a robotaxi service, but wa=
s owned and funded by a car maker, which said service layer should have bee=
n commoditizing! In other words, while you can make an argument that GM wan=
ts to avoid being a commodity car provider to future Robotaxi services, tha=
t desire =E2=80=94 assuming they expected Cruise to only work with GM cars =
=E2=80=94=C2=A0would have fundamentally handicapped Cruise in the long run.=
 More prosaically, GM wasn=E2=80=99t really providing anything of value to =
Cruise other than funding, and wasn=E2=80=99t receiving anything other than=
 good PR=E2=80=A6oh wait, bad PR, given Cruise=E2=80=99s pedestrian inciden=
t last year. And now that funding is no more.

Instead GM is doing what makes much more sense given their position in the =
stack: focusing on developing autonomous technology that will ideally make =
their cars more differentiated to consumers, allowing them to charge a prem=
ium. However, as I noted at the beginning, it=E2=80=99s not clear how much =
of Cruise=E2=80=99s technology will translate; I highly doubt there will be=
 $9 billion worth of value.

Robotaxi Outlook
----------------

So what of the Robotaxi market now? Has Waymo won? Can Zoox, which is set t=
o launch a robotaxi service in Las Vegas early next year ( https://www.ktnv=
.com/news/how-one-company-plans-to-introduce-a-new-robotaxi-to-the-las-vega=
s-strip ) , provide a challenge? What about Tesla?

In fact, I think this view misses the point; robotaxis are a technology, no=
t a market =E2=80=94 a means, not an end, if you will. Markets are defined =
by demand, and the demand to be tapped is transportation. And, in this mark=
et, the dominant player is Uber; no they don=E2=80=99t have their own robot=
axis, but from a consumer perspective, they might as well: the rider doesn=
=E2=80=99t own the vehicle they ride in, they summon it from an app, and th=
ey just walk away when the ride is done. The experience =E2=80=94 if not th=
e novelty =E2=80=94 is the same with a human driver or a robotaxi.

Moreover, the human drivers come with some big advantages from Uber=E2=80=
=99s perspective: they bear their own depreciation costs, and can make indi=
vidual decisions about the marginal rate necessary to provide supply, which=
 is another way of saying that Uber can more easily scale up and down to me=
et demand by using price as a signal. It is an open question as to whether =
robotaxis can ever economically scale to meet demand: having enough capacit=
y for peak demand means a lot of robotaxis sitting idle a lot of the time, =
while maximizing utilization means insufficient supply during peak periods.

This last point is why my assumption is that Uber will very much be relevan=
t in the robotaxi era: their supply network will be essential for scaling u=
p-and-down within cities, and serving all of the areas that the centralized=
 fleets do not. What is less clear is their long-term profitability, which =
may be somewhat out of their control.

First, Waymo (or Zoox, or other alternatives), may choose to focus on their=
 own networks, as Waymo is doing in San Francisco. This will force consumer=
s to multihome, at least if they prefer a robotaxi to an Uber; they can che=
ck Waymo first, and if it isn=E2=80=99t available or doesn=E2=80=99t go whe=
re they need to go, they can switch to Uber. I do think this is less likely=
, however: remember, robotaxis need to maximize utilization, which means it=
 will be better to be on the more full-service platform that is likely to a=
ttract the greatest demand; to that end, it makes sense that Waymo is enter=
ing cities like Atlanta and Austin in partnership with Uber.

Still, that doesn=E2=80=99t answer Uber=E2=80=99s long-term profitability q=
uestion. Uber=E2=80=99s profitability has increased as it has slowly won th=
e demand aggregation war with Lyft, and thus gained increased pricing power=
 over fully atomized supply; a robotaxi supplier, however, would have signi=
ficantly more bargaining power, since it is basically a single entity repre=
senting hundreds or thousands of =E2=80=9Cdrivers=E2=80=9D, which will prob=
ably offer a superior user experience (and thus is a threat to compete). Th=
at would diminish Uber=E2=80=99s profitability.

Tesla is definitely a wild card in all of this. Elon Musk has proposed the =
idea of individual Tesla owners renting out their cars on a Tesla-operated =
service when they=E2=80=99re not using them, but I=E2=80=99m skeptical abou=
t how attractive that would be to car owners; if you wanted to use a robota=
xi all of the time =E2=80=94 which your car now is =E2=80=94 why not just u=
se a robotaxi service? Is Tesla going to actually incur the costs of owning=
 and operating an always-available fleet?

What potentially makes more sense is small-scale fleet owners that own a sm=
all number of Teslas that they maintain and put on a transportation network=
, but then we are back to the utilization question and the desire to be on =
a network that has superior demand. What probably makes the most sense is s=
elf-driving Teslas on Uber, right alongside human drivers, who will slowly =
be competed out of the service as increased autonomous supply drives down p=
rices =E2=80=94 which would be good for Uber.

Of course this is all dependent on Tesla self-driving actually becoming ful=
ly autonomous, thanks to Elon Dreams and Bitter Lessons ( https://strateche=
ry.com/2024/elon-dreams-and-bitter-lessons/?access_token=3DeyJhbGciOiJSUzI1=
